Substratum: large Fagus sylvatica trunk in its late disintegration state lying on ground.

Place: Lower Trenta valley, between villages Soča and Trenta, left bank of river Soča, 200 m upstream from Matevž’s (Trenta 1) footbridge, between Soča trail and the river, East Julian Alps, Posočje, Slovenia.

Description: about 12 pilei present, from 3 to 6.3 cm wide and 2 to 3.8 cm from substrate; pilei cutis dry, not waxy, doesn’t peel away; smell and taste indistinctive; 10% KOH reaction on gills reddish; SP abundant, brown, oac784.

Camera: Sony ILCE6000 / Carl Zeiss Vario-Tessar E 16-70 mm/f4

results.notes:
Growing on a Carpinus caroliniana leaf. Subiculum absent. Apothecia sessile and white with hairy margins; up to 0.4 mm wide. Ectal excipulum a hyaline textura angularis. Hairs smooth and thin-walled; with curled or filiform apice; with a brown refractive content basally in Melzer’s; septate. Paraphyses cylindrical and also containing brown refractive material in Melzer’s. Asci inoperculate; with amyloid apical plugs; 4-spored; with croziers. Spores hyaline, smooth, fusiform to slightly falcate, and 0-septate. Spore measurements: (12.1) 12.6 – 15.4 (15.7) × (1.8) 2 – 2.4 (2.6) µm; Q = (5.6) 5.7 – 7.2 (7.6); N = 30; Me = 13.9 × 2.2 µm; Qe = 6.5

results.notes:
This is one of 3 Dermatocarpon I found on a seasonal, south-facing seep of cobble conglomerate. All 3 (see other entries of same date) are small (less than 2 cm) with multiple holdfasts. This is the smallest, all lobes under 15 mm. As seen from photos, this thallus is a bright olive green when wet, and stays olive but is significantly dark brown when dry. Underside is buff when dry but almost a golden salmon color when wet. Perethecia are sparse, but present. NO pruina on upper or lower surface; no rhizines. In the habitat, it preferred the deepest crevasses in the rock faces, the most sheltered overhangs with the most flow.

This is the species it keyed out to, but I’d love to hear other opinions!

results.notes:
This very robust and oversized (monstrous is a better word) grisette – this may well be the largest sect. Vaginatae I’ve ever seen – was growing in the disturbed soil and needle duff of the northern bank of Coopers Rd. (between Pakim Pond and Muddy Rd. crossing). The habitat is mostly pine with some scrub oak intermixed here and there, which is very typical for the heart of the Pine Barrens region of NJ. Some white pine is also present in the general area.
I was very surprised to find this yet to be identified sect. Vaginatae fruiting so late in the season in this habitat. In my experience, the only species from this section of Amanita that fruits so late in the Pinelands is A. variicolor (= RETs’ dulciarii / vulpecula by DNA), and even mid-November is pretty late for it. However, this observation is not A. variicolor on account the well-formed and thick-walled volval sack that variicolor lacks and the very large fruitbody size, though the orangish snake-skin ornamentation on the stipe is quite reminiscent of this species.
The recorded dimensions are as follows:
> Cap = 8-9 cm wide (though it was probably wider, as the margins are frayed and the striations are too short vis-a-vis the cap radius)
> Stipe = 21 cm long (!), ~1.3 cm wide at the narrowest position (just below the flaring apex) and ~2.5 cm wide just above the rim of the volval sack
> Volva = 6 cm tall, 3.5 cm wide max; sack wall thickness = 2.5-3 mm max
Considering the very large size and post-mature condition of the mushroom, it must have fruited a few days prior, though many flimsier grisettes grow and mature within a day and don’t really last more than a couple of days, especially in hot and humid weather. It rained heavily at BBSF the day before, so the basidiome’s cap took a beating from the severe weather, and its appearance is reflective of this. I am wondering if the rain also allowed the mushroom to attain its impressive size.
Unfortunately, I didn’t have my camera with me when I stumbled upon this critter, and by the time I got home it was too dark to take photos in natural light. The attached images were taken indoors (incadescent light) with a flash, so the colors are richer than they should be. The cap was dark yellowish-brown / dark caramel brown. The gills dried dark cream.
